{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_0","type":"agent_message","text":"**Topology Summary**\n\nUse a first-order passive RC low-pass: `R1 = 1 kOhm` in series from `Vin` to `Vout`, and `C1 = 1 uF` from `Vout` to ground `0`. Drive `Vin` with a ground-referenced independent AC source. This realizes a single-pole low-pass with corner frequency near `1 / (2*pi*R1*C1) â‰ˆ 159 Hz`.\n\n**Device / Function List**\n\n- `V1`: independent AC voltage source, drives `Vin` relative to `0`\n- `R1`: series element between `Vin` and `Vout`; with `C1` sets the pole\n- `C1`: shunt capacitor from `Vout` to `0`; bypasses high-frequency content to ground\n- `0`: only reference node / ground\n\n**Bias / Reference Strategy**\n\nNo supply rails or active biasing are needed. Use node `0` as the only reference. The input must not float: the AC source should connect directly to `Vin` and `0`. Small-signal AC excitation is sufficient.\n\n**Signal / Feedback Path**\n\nSignal path is `Vin -> R1 -> Vout`.  \nThere is no active feedback loop; the only frequency-dependent return path is the passive shunt through `C1` from `Vout` to ground. At low frequency, `C1` is effectively open so `Vout ~ Vin`; at high frequency, `C1` increasingly shorts `Vout` to ground, reducing output.\n\n**SPICE / Netlist Constraints**\n\n- Preserve exact node names `Vin` and `Vout`\n- Both `Vin` and `Vout` must appear explicitly as named nodes\n- Use only primitive devices: independent source, resistor, capacitor\n- Keep the intended analysis as `.ac dec 20 1 1e9`\n- Do not introduce behavioral elements, controlled sources, or extra parasitics unless explicitly requested\n\n**Failure Risks to Avoid**\n\n- Do not swap resistor/capacitor placement; that can change the response or create a high-pass topology\n- Do not place the output on the wrong side of `R1`; `Vout` must be the RC junction\n- Do not leave `Vin` undriven or floating\n- Do not rename `Vin` or `Vout`\n- Do not add unintended load resistance at `Vout`, since it will shift the pole and reduce low-frequency gain\n- Do not add source resistance in series with the AC source unless that change is intentional, because it alters the effective `R` and cutoff frequency\n\nExpected AC behavior: near-unity gain at low frequency, about `-3 dB` near `159-160 Hz`, and asymptotic `-20 dB/decade` roll-off above the pole."}}
